0–Deceased","1330":"1330","1286":"1286","1285":"1285","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1279":"1279","1453":"1453","1298":"1298","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England":"Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England","Bromley, London, England":"Bromley, London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bromley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Bromley, in Essex, Hertfordshire, Kent (now in Greater London), Greater London, Greater Manchester, Staffordshire, Shropshire, and elsewhere. Most are named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, but Bromley (near Bow) in Greater London is from Old English <i>bræmbel</i> ‘bramble’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Brimley","meanings":["habitational name, perhaps from Brimley in Devon or Brimbley in Stoke Abbott, Dorset, both named with Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","variant of   Bromley  .","English:"]},{"name":"Brumley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bromley  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":17,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":30,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":39,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":84,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Bromley was born in 1298, in Baddington, Cheshire, England, his father, Ranulph De Bromlegh, was 14 and his mother, Ann De Ipstones, was 39. He married Mrs. Lady Thomas Bromley in 1318, in Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Bromley in Eccleshall, Staffordshire, England."},"et":{"1298–":"1298–Surnud","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1281–1339":"1281–1339","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1303–Fema